<https://n2t.net/ark:/27023/684a03874c94b162ddf318b849877ba2> <https://colonialcollections.nl/schema#description> "Beschrijvingskaart:\r\nGootvormige aangepunte spits van bamboe, het ondereinde met puntig vlechtwerk en omwoeling verbonden aan een cylindrisch tussenstuk van palmhout waarin ingesneden rijen spiralen. Aan het ondereind hiervan een omwikkeling van lianen. Rotan schacht met ingegrifte versiering, brede langstrepen met voet en groepen fijne en brede ringen.\r\n\r\nThe arrows consist generally of two component parts, the head of the bamboo or palm wood, either hardened in the fire or not, and the shaft, made of cane. Not seldom however a fore shaft is introduced in between, and sometimes a special tip is fastened on to the arrow head. \r\nThere are several kinds of arrows depending on the use. They were used to hunt, to fish and to fight. \r\nBows and arrows could be deposited in the grave of its wearer after his death. At Asei, in the fence around a grave, the bow of the death man is stuck straight into the soil (See Sande, 1907, p. 271, fig. 166)\r\nSande noticed that arms were always carried when going outside the village, and the women working in the gardens were accompanied by men in case of an attack.\r\n\r\nArrows for pig hunting always have a bamboo head, making a large wound. The profuse loss of blood permits to find the animal easily and prevent its escape too far in the bush." .
